= Heat Transfer Modes

Energy can be transferred as heat through three primary mechanisms: conduction, convection, and radiation.

== Convection
Heat transfer between a solid surface and a moving fluid.
$ dot(Q)_"conv" = alpha A (T_s - T_f) $
where $alpha$ is the heat transfer coefficient and $A$ is the surface area. The rate of cooling depends linearly on the temperature difference ($Delta T$).

== Radiation
Energy emission via electromagnetic waves. All matter with a temperature above absolute zero emits radiation.
$ dot(Q)_"rad" = epsilon sigma A (T^4 - T_0^4) $
where $sigma$ is the Stefan-Boltzmann constant ($5.67 times 10^(-8) " W m"^(-2) "K"^(-4)$) and $epsilon$ is the emissivity. Radiation is highly sensitive to the absolute temperature due to the $T^4$ dependence.

== Minimizing Heat Loss
To keep a substance hot, one should minimize the temperature gradient $(T - T_0)$ early in the process. Mixing a cold substance (like milk) into a hot one (like coffee) immediately lowers the initial temperature, reducing both convective and radiative losses during the waiting period.
